Internet Research Agency Tweets over Time

This is a time-series analysis of 203.482 tweets from 8.458 users that are suspected of being part of the Internet Research Agency (IRA). The dataset is based on actions taken by Twitter and was curated by NBC News, which made the data available here. To generate this visualization we create an extension of the Mapper algorithm (pdf paper) and combine it with traditional analysis methods.

We show the number of Tweets per day as a proxy for IRA activity. We include some key events in US politics. We cover this projection with overlapping intervals. Every interval contains 7 days and overlaps with the 4 previous and next intervals. Every interval forms a node. The inverse image is a 1000-dimensional one-hot encoded array with TF-IDF on the Tweet tokens. We create 5 clusters per interval with agglomerative clustering. Edges hold information on shifts in distribution. Descriptive statistics are provided for the intervals, clusters, and edges.

Code to replicate this visualization will be released soon. The code uses Python, Numpy, Scikit-learn, Jupyter Notebook, and Pandas. Note: May contain mild profanity.

Discussion

We see a clear correlation between key events in US politics and IRA tweet activity. For instance, the organization of rallies and activism coincides with tweet topics.

The topics that form show that IRA played both sides: #imwithher vs. #lockherup, #blacklivesmatter vs. #bluelivesmatter, or 'racism at the oscars' vs. #oscarshavenocolor. Activity increases during the presidential debates (often with a short delay of a few days), and special attention is put on promotion of the hacked emails. The focus is not solely on US politics, but also includes mentions of the German Chancellor Merkel and the Brussels terrorist attacks. In general, this visualization shows that the main IRA tactic is to promote divisive topics on both sides of the political spectrum: children detainees, immigrants, terrorists, abortion, Iran nuclear deal, police shootings, BLM activism, Comey, etcetera.
